  </interactive>
</figure>

<m>\mbox{span}\left(\begin{bmatrix}1\\2\\-1\end{bmatrix},\begin{bmatrix}2\\0\\1\end{bmatrix},\begin{bmatrix}4\\4\\-1\end{bmatrix}\right)</m> is \wordChoice{\choice{A line}, \choice[correct]{A plane}, \choice{<m>\R^3</m>}, \choice{A parallelepiped}}


Can we remove one of the vectors from the set without changing the span?  Observe that we can write <m>\begin{bmatrix}4\\4\\-1\end{bmatrix}</m> as a linear combination of the other two vectors
 <men>\label{eq:redundant}\begin{bmatrix}4\\4\\-1\end{bmatrix}=2\begin{bmatrix}1\\2\\-1\end{bmatrix}+1\begin{bmatrix}2\\0\\1\end{bmatrix}</men>

 This means that we can write any vector in <m>\mbox{span}\left(\begin{bmatrix}1\\2\\-1\end{bmatrix},\begin{bmatrix}2\\0\\1\end{bmatrix},\begin{bmatrix}4\\4\\-1\end{bmatrix}\right)</m> as a linear combination of only <m>\begin{bmatrix}1\\2\\-1\end{bmatrix}</m> and <m>\begin{bmatrix}2\\0\\1\end{bmatrix}</m> by replacing <m>\begin{bmatrix}4\\4\\-1\end{bmatrix}</m> with the expression in (<xref ref="eq-redundant"/>). For example, 
<me>
    \begin{bmatrix}7\\6\\-1\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}1\\2\\-1\end{bmatrix}+\begin{bmatrix}2\\0\\1\end{bmatrix}+\begin{bmatrix}4\\4\\-1\end{bmatrix}=3\begin{bmatrix}1\\2\\-1\end{bmatrix}+2\begin{bmatrix}2\\0\\1\end{bmatrix}
</me>


We have

<me>
    \mbox{span}\left(\begin{bmatrix}1\\2\\-1\end{bmatrix},\begin{bmatrix}2\\0\\1\end{bmatrix},\begin{bmatrix}4\\4\\-1\end{bmatrix}\right)=\mbox{span}\left(\begin{bmatrix}1\\2\\-1\end{bmatrix},\begin{bmatrix}2\\0\\1\end{bmatrix}\right)
</me>


 We conclude that vector <m>\begin{bmatrix}4\\4\\-1\end{bmatrix}</m> is redundant.  Can each of the other two vectors in the set 
 <m>\left\{\begin{bmatrix}1\\2\\-1\end{bmatrix},\begin{bmatrix}2\\0\\1\end{bmatrix},\begin{bmatrix}4\\4\\-1\end{bmatrix}\right\}</m> be considered redundant?  You will address this question in Practice Problem <xref ref="prob-redundant1"/>.
    </p>
</exploration>
 
<p>
 Collections of vectors that do not contain redundant vectors are very important in linear algebra.  We will refer to such collections as <term>linearly independent</term>.  Collections of vectors that contain redundant vectors will be called <term>linearly dependent</term>.  The following section offers a definition that will allow us to easily determine linear dependence and independence of vectors.
</p>
</subsection>



<subsection xml:id="Subsection-Linear-Independence">
    <title>Linear Independence</title>


<definition xml:id="def-linearindependence">
    <title>Linear Independence</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Let <m>\mathbf{v}_1, \mathbf{v}_2,\ldots ,\mathbf{v}_k</m> be vectors of <m>\R^n</m>.  We say that the set <m>\{\mathbf{v}_1, \mathbf{v}_2,\ldots ,\mathbf{v}_k\}</m> is <term>linearly independent</term> if the only solution to 
<men>\label{eq:defLinInd}c_1\mathbf{v}_1+c_2\mathbf{v}_2+\ldots +c_p\mathbf{v}_k=\mathbf{0}</men>
is the <term>trivial solution</term> <m>c_1=c_2=\ldots =c_k=0</m>.

If, in addition to the trivial solution, a <term>non-trivial solution</term> (not all <m>c_1, c_2,\ldots ,c_k</m> are zero) exists, then we say that the set <m>\{\mathbf{v}_1, \mathbf{v}_2,\ldots ,\mathbf{v}_k\}</m> is <term>linearly dependent</term>.
        </p>
    </statement>
</definition>

<remark xml:id="LinIndEquiv">
<p>
Given a set of vectors <m>X=\{\mathbf{v}_1,\mathbf{v}_2,\dots,\mathbf{v}_k\}</m> we can now ask the following questions:
<ol>
<li>
      <p> Are the vectors in <m>X</m> linearly dependent according to Definition <xref ref="def-linearindependence"/>? </p>
</li>
<li>
      <p> Can we write one element of <m>X</m> as a linear combination of the others? </p>
</li>
    <li>
      <p> Does <m>X</m> contain redundant vectors? </p>
</li>
</ol>
It turns out that these questions are equivalent.  In other words, if the answer to one of them is ``YES", the answer to the other two is also ``YES".  Conversely, if the answer to one of them is ``NO", then the answer to the other two is also ``NO".  We will start by illustrating this idea with an example, then conclude this section by formally proving the equivalency.
</p>
</remark>

<example xml:id="ex-linind">
    <statement>
        <p>
            What can we say about the following sets of vectors in light of Remark <xref ref="remark-LinIndEquiv"/>?

<ol>
<li xml:id="item-linindpart1">
  <p> \label{item:linindpart1}

<me> </p>
</li>
    \begin{bmatrix}2\\-3\end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix}0\\3\end{bmatrix},\begin{bmatrix}1\\-1\end{bmatrix},\begin{bmatrix}1\\-2\end{bmatrix}
</me>


<li xml:id="item-linindpart2">
  <p> \label{item:linindpart2} 
<me> </p>
</li>
    \begin{bmatrix}2\\1\\4\end{bmatrix},\begin{bmatrix}-3\\1\\1\end{bmatrix}
</me>

</ol>
       </p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
        <p>
            <xref ref="item-linindpart1"/>
We will start by addressing linear independence.  To do so, we will solve the vector equation
<mdn>\label{eq:linrelationpart1}c_1\begin{bmatrix}2\\-3\end{bmatrix}+c_2 \begin{bmatrix}0\\3\end{bmatrix}+c_3\begin{bmatrix}1\\-1\end{bmatrix}+c_4\begin{bmatrix}1\\-2\end{bmatrix}=\mathbf{0}</mdn>
 
 Clearly <m>c_1=c_2=c_3=c_4=0</m> is a solution to the equation.  The question is whether another solution exists.
 
The vector equation translates into the following system:


<me>
    \begin{array}{ccccccccc}
      2c_1 \amp  \amp \amp +\amp c_3\amp +\amp c_4\amp = \amp 0 \\
        -3c_1\amp  +\amp 3c_2\amp -\amp c_3\amp -\amp 2c_4\amp = \amp 0 \\
      \end{array}
</me>

  Writing the system in augmented matrix form and applying elementary row operations gives us the following reduced row-echelon form:
  
<me>
    \left[\begin{array}{cccc|c}  
 2\amp 0\amp 1\amp 1\amp 0\\-3\amp 3\amp -1\amp -2\amp 0
 \end{array}\right]\rightsquigarrow\left[\begin{array}{cccc|c}  
 1\amp 0\amp 1/2\amp 1/2\amp 0\\0\amp 1\amp 1/6\amp -1/6\amp 0
 \end{array}\right]
</me>

 This shows that (<xref ref="eq-linrelationpart1"/>) has infinitely many solutions:  
 
<me>
    c_1=-\frac{1}{2}s-\frac{1}{2}t,\quad c_2=-\frac{1}{6}s+\frac{1}{6}t,\quad c_3=s,\quad c_4=t
</me>

 Letting <m>t=s=6</m>, we obtain the following:
 
 <men>\label{eq:ex1}
 -6\begin{bmatrix}2\\-3\end{bmatrix}+0 \begin{bmatrix}0\\3\end{bmatrix}+6\begin{bmatrix}1\\-1\end{bmatrix}+6\begin{bmatrix}1\\-2\end{bmatrix}=\mathbf{0}
 </men>
 We conclude that the vectors are linearly dependent.

 Observe that (<xref ref="eq-ex1"/>)  allows us to solve for one of the vectors and express it as a linear combination of the others. For example, 
<men>\label{eq:ex1lincomb}
    \begin{bmatrix}2\\-3\end{bmatrix}=0 \begin{bmatrix}0\\3\end{bmatrix}+\begin{bmatrix}1\\-1\end{bmatrix}+\begin{bmatrix}1\\-2\end{bmatrix}
</men>
This would not be possible if a nontrivial solution to the equation

<me>
    c_1\begin{bmatrix}2\\-3\end{bmatrix}+c_2 \begin{bmatrix}0\\3\end{bmatrix}+c_3\begin{bmatrix}1\\-1\end{bmatrix}+c_4\begin{bmatrix}1\\-2\end{bmatrix}=\mathbf{0}
</me>

did not exist.

Using the linear combination in (<xref ref="eq-ex1lincomb"/>) and the argument of Exploration <xref ref="exp-redundantVecs2"/>, we conclude that <m>\begin{bmatrix}2\\-3\end{bmatrix}</m> is redundant in 

<me>
    \left\{\begin{bmatrix}2\\-3\end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix}0\\3\end{bmatrix},\begin{bmatrix}1\\-1\end{bmatrix},\begin{bmatrix}1\\-2\end{bmatrix}\right\}
</me>

We find that the answer to all questions in Remark <xref ref="remark-LinIndEquiv"/> is ``YES".
 
 
 <xref ref="item-linindpart2"/> To address linear independence, we need to solve the equation
 
 
<me>
    c_1\begin{bmatrix}2\\1\\4\end{bmatrix}+c_2\begin{bmatrix}-3\\1\\1\end{bmatrix}=\mathbf{0}
</me>

 Converting the equation to augmented matrix form and performing row reduction gives us
 
<me>
    \left[\begin{array}{cc|c}  
 2\amp -3\amp 0\\1\amp 1\amp 0\\4\amp 1\amp 0
 \end{array}\right]\rightsquigarrow\left[\begin{array}{cc|c}  
 1\amp 0\amp 0\\0\amp 1\amp 0\\0\amp 0\amp 0
 \end{array}\right]
</me>

 This shows that <m>c_1=c_2=0</m> is the only solution.  Therefore the two vectors are linearly independent.
 
 Furthermore, we cannot write one of the vectors as a linear combination of the other.  (Do you see that the only way this would be possible with a set of two vectors is if they were scalar multiples of each other?)
 
Finally, we observe that removing either vector would change the span from a plane in <m>\R^3</m> to a line in <m>\R^3</m>, so the answer to all three questions in Remark <xref ref="remark-LinIndEquiv"/> is ``NO".
       </p>
    </answer>
</example>



<theorem xml:id="th-lindeplincombofother">

    <statement>
        <p>
            Let <m>\mathbf{v}_1,\mathbf{v}_2,\dots ,\mathbf{v}_k</m> be  a set of vectors in <m>\R^n</m> containing two or more vectors.  The following conditions are equivalent.
<ol>
<li xml:id="th-lindeplincombofother_a">
  <p> \label{th:lindeplincombofother_a} 
%There exists a non-trivial solution to <m>c_1\mathbf{v}_1+c_2\mathbf{v}_2+\dots +c_k\mathbf{v}_k=\mathbf{0}</m>.
<m>\mathbf{v}_1,\mathbf{v}_2,\dots ,\mathbf{v}_k</m> are linearly dependent. </p>
</li>
<li xml:id="th-lindeplincombofother_b">
  <p> \label{th:lindeplincombofother_b} 
One of <m>\mathbf{v}_1,\mathbf{v}_2,\dots ,\mathbf{v}_k</m> can be expressed as a linear combination of the others. </p>
</li>
<li xml:id="th-lindeplincombofother_c">
  <p> \label{th:lindeplincombofother_c} 
The set <m>\{\mathbf{v}_1,\mathbf{v}_2,\dots ,\mathbf{v}_k\}</m> contains redundant vectors. </p>
</li>
</ol>
        </p>
    </statement>
</theorem>

<proof>
    <p>
 <xref ref="th-lindeplincombofother_a"/> <m>\implies</m> <xref ref="th-lindeplincombofother_b"/>  If <m>\mathbf{v}_1,\mathbf{v}_2,\dots ,\mathbf{v}_k</m> are linearly dependent, then 
 <me>c_1\mathbf{v}_1+c_2\mathbf{v}_2+\ldots +c_j\mathbf{v}_j+\ldots +c_k\mathbf{v}_k=\mathbf{0}</me>
 
 has a non-trivial solution.  In other words at least one of the constants, say <m>c_j</m>, does not equal zero.  This allows us to solve for <m>\mathbf{v}_j</m>:

<md>
-c_j\mathbf{v}_j\amp =c_1\mathbf{v}_1+c_2\mathbf{v}_2+\ldots +c_k\mathbf{v}_k \\ \\
\mathbf{v}_j\amp =-\frac{c_1}{c_j}\mathbf{v}_1-\frac{c_2}{c_j}\mathbf{v}_2-\ldots -\frac{c_k}{c_j}\mathbf{v}_k
</md>
(Do you see why it was important to have one of the constants nonzero?)  This shows that <m>\mathbf{v}_j</m> may be expressed as a linear combination of the other vectors.

<xref ref="th-lindeplincombofother_b"/> <m>\implies</m> <xref ref="th-lindeplincombofother_c"/>  First, suppose <m>\mathbf{v}_j</m> is a linear combination of <m>\mathbf{v}_1,\mathbf{v}_2,\dots,\mathbf{v}_k</m>.  We will show that <m>\mathbf{v}_j</m> is redundant by showing that 
<me>
    \mbox{span}\left(\mathbf{v}_1,\mathbf{v}_2,\dots,\mathbf{v}_k\right)=\mbox{span}\left(\mathbf{v}_1,\mathbf{v}_2,\dots,\mathbf{v}_{j-1},\mathbf{v}_{j+1},\dots,\mathbf{v}_k\right).
</me>

To show equality of the two spans we will pick a vector in the left span and show that it is also an element of the span on the right.  Then, we will pick a vector in the right span and show that it is also an element of the span on the left, and we will conclude that the sets are equal.

Observe that if <m>\mathbf{w}</m> is in <m>\mbox{span}\left(\mathbf{v}_1,\mathbf{v}_2,\dots,\mathbf{v}_{j-1},\mathbf{v}_{j+1},\dots,\mathbf{v}_k\right)</m>, then it has to be in <m>\mbox{span}\left(\mathbf{v}_1,\mathbf{v}_2,\dots,\mathbf{v}_k\right)</m>. (Why?)

Now suppose <m>\mathbf{w}</m> is in <m>\mbox{span}\left(\mathbf{v}_1,\mathbf{v}_2,\dots,\mathbf{v}_k\right)</m>.  We need to show that <m>\mathbf{w}</m> is also in <m>\mbox{span}\left(\mathbf{v}_1,\mathbf{v}_2,\dots,\mathbf{v}_{j-1},\mathbf{v}_{j+1},\dots,\mathbf{v}_k\right)</m>.

By assumption, we can write <m>\mathbf{v}_j</m> as
<men>\label{eq:vj}
\mathbf{v}_j=a_1\mathbf{v}_1+a_2\mathbf{v}_2+\dots +a_{j-1}\mathbf{v}_{j-1}+a_{j+1}\mathbf{v}_{j+1}+\dots +a_k\mathbf{v}_k.
</men>

Since <m>\mathbf{w}</m> is in <m>\mbox{span}\left(\mathbf{v}_1,\mathbf{v}_2,\dots,\mathbf{v}_k\right)</m>, we have

<me>
    \mathbf{w}=b_1\mathbf{v}_1+b_2\mathbf{v}_2+\dots +b_j\mathbf{v}_j+\dots +b_k\mathbf{v}_k.
</me>

Substituting the expression in (<xref ref="eq-vj"/>) for <m>\mathbf{v}_j</m> and simplifying, we obtain the following
\begin{eqnarray*}\mathbf{w}=(b_1+b_ja_1)\mathbf{v}_1+(b_2+b_ja_2)\mathbf{v}_2\amp +\amp \dots\\
\amp +\amp (b_{j-1}+b_ja_{j-1})\mathbf{v}_{j-1}\\
\amp +\amp (b_{j+1}+b_ja_{j+1})\mathbf{v}_{j+1}\\
\amp +\amp \dots\\
\amp +\amp (b_k+b_ja_k)\mathbf{v}_k.\end{eqnarray*}
This shows that <m>\mathbf{w}</m> is in <m>\mbox{span}\left(\mathbf{v}_1,\mathbf{v}_2,\dots,\mathbf{v}_{j-1},\mathbf{v}_{j+1},\dots,\mathbf{v}_k\right)</m>.
We now have 

<me>
    \mbox{span}\left(\mathbf{v}_1,\mathbf{v}_2,\dots,\mathbf{v}_k\right)=\mbox{span}\left(\mathbf{v}_1,\mathbf{v}_2,\dots,\mathbf{v}_{j-1},\mathbf{v}_{j+1},\dots,\mathbf{v}_k\right),
</me>

which shows that <m>\mathbf{v}_j</m> is redundant.

 <xref ref="th-lindeplincombofother_c"/> <m>\implies</m> <xref ref="th-lindeplincombofother_a"/>  Suppose that <m>\mathbf{v}_j</m> is redundant, so that
 
<me>
    \mbox{span}\left(\mathbf{v}_1,\mathbf{v}_2,\dots,\mathbf{v}_k\right)=\mbox{span}\left(\mathbf{v}_1,\mathbf{v}_2,\dots,\mathbf{v}_{j-1},\mathbf{v}_{j+1},\dots,\mathbf{v}_k\right).
</me>

 Consider a vector <m>\mathbf{w}</m> in <m>\mbox{span}\left(\mathbf{v}_1,\mathbf{v}_2,\dots,\mathbf{v}_k\right)</m>  
<men>\label{eq:w1}
\mathbf{w}=a_1\mathbf{v}_1+a_2\mathbf{v}_2+\dots +a_j\mathbf{v}_j+\dots +a_k\mathbf{v}_k
</men>
Since the span contains ALL possible linear combinations of <m>\mathbf{v}_1,\mathbf{v}_2,\dots,\mathbf{v}_k</m>, we may choose <m>\mathbf{w}</m> such that <m>a_j\neq 0</m>.

By assumption, <m>\mathbf{w}</m> is also in <m>\mbox{span}\left(\mathbf{v}_1,\mathbf{v}_2,\dots,\mathbf{v}_{j-1},\mathbf{v}_{j+1},\dots,\mathbf{v}_k\right)</m>.  Therefore, we can express <m>\mathbf{w}</m> as a linear combination 
<men>\label{eq:w2}
\mathbf{w}=b_1\mathbf{v}_1+b_2\mathbf{v}_2+\dots +b_{j-1}\mathbf{v}_{j-1}+b_{j+1}\mathbf{v}_{j+1}+\dots +b_k\mathbf{v}_k.
</men>

 We complete the proof by showing there exists a non-trivial solution to 
<men>\label{eq:LinIndepDefRepeated}
c_1\mathbf{v}_1+c_2\mathbf{v}_2+\ldots +c_j\mathbf{v}_j+\ldots +c_k\mathbf{v}_k=\mathbf{0}.</men>  Subtracting expression (<xref ref="eq-w2"/>) from (<xref ref="eq-w1"/>) we obtain
\begin{eqnarray*}
    \mathbf{0}=\mathbf{w}-\mathbf{w}=(a_1-b_1)\mathbf{v}_1\amp +\amp \dots\\ \nonumber
    \amp +\amp (a_{j-1}-b_{j-1})\mathbf{v}_{j-1}+a_j\mathbf{v}_j+(a_{j+1}-b_{j+1})\mathbf{v}_{j+1}\\ \nonumber
  \amp +\amp \dots\\ \nonumber
  \amp +\amp (a_k-b_k)\mathbf{v}_k
\end{eqnarray*}
Recall that we ensured that <m>a_j\neq 0</m>.  This implies that we have a non-trivial solution to Equation <xref ref="eq-LinIndepDefRepeated"/>.

These three parts of the proof show that if one of the conditions is true, all three must be true.  It is a logical consequence that if one of the three conditions is false, all three must be false.
     </p>
</proof>
</subsection>






 
<subsection xml:id="Subsection-Geometry-of-Linearly-Dependent-and-Linearly-Independent-Vectors">
    <title>Geometry of Linearly Dependent and Linearly Independent Vectors</title>

<p>
Theorem <xref ref="th-lindeplincombofother"/> gives us a convenient ways of looking at linear dependence/independence geometrically.  When looking at two or more vectors, we ask, ``can one of the vectors be written as a linear combination of the others?"  We can also ask, ``is one of the vectors redundant?''  If the answer to either of these questions is ``YES", then the vectors are linearly dependent.
</p>

<subsubsection xml:id="Subsubsection-A-Set-of-Two-Vectors">
    <title>A Set of Two Vectors</title>
 <p>   
Two vectors are linearly dependent if and only if one is a scalar multiple of the other.  Two nonzero linearly dependent vectors may look like this:
\begin{center}
<image width="100%">
   <shortdescription>Two vectors drawn</shortdescription>
    <latex-image>
      \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
% \draw[\lt -\gt ] (-0.5,0)--(2.5,0);
 % \draw[\lt -\gt ] (0,-0.5)--(0,2.5);
    \draw[line width=1pt,blue,-stealth](0,0)--(2,2);
  \draw[line width=1pt,red,-stealth](0,0)--(1,1);
     \end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
</image>
\end{center}
or like this:
\begin{center}
<image width="100%">
   <shortdescription>One vector flipped</shortdescription>
    <latex-image>
      \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
%\draw[\lt -\gt ] (-2.5,0)--(2.5,0);
 % \draw[\lt -\gt ] (0,-2.5)--(0,2.5);
    \draw[line width=1pt,blue,-stealth](0,0)--(1,2);
  \draw[line width=1pt,red,-stealth](0,0)--(-0.5,-1);
     \end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
</image>
\end{center}
Two linearly independent vectors will look like this:
\begin{center}
<image width="100%">
   <shortdescription>One vector rotated</shortdescription>
    <latex-image>
      \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
%\draw[\lt -\gt ] (-2.5,0)--(2.5,0);
 % \draw[\lt -\gt ] (0,-2.5)--(0,2.5);
    \draw[line width=1pt,blue,-stealth](0,0)--(1,1);
  \draw[line width=1pt,red,-stealth](0,0)--(0.5,-1);
     \end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
</image>
\end{center}
</p>
</subsubsection>



<subsubsection xml: id="Subsubsection-A-Set-of-Three-Vectors">
    <title>A Set of Three Vectors</title>
<p>
Given a set of three nonzero vectors, we have the following possibilities: 
<ul>
<li>
      <p> (Linearly Dependent Vectors)
The three vectors are scalar multiples of each other. </p>
</li>
\begin{center}
<image width="100%">
   <shortdescription></shortdescription>
    <latex-image>
      \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
% \draw[\lt -\gt ] (-0.5,0)--(2.5,0);
 % \draw[\lt -\gt ] (0,-0.5)--(0,2.5);
    \draw[line width=1pt,blue,-stealth](0,0)--(2,2);
  \draw[line width=1pt,red,-stealth](0,0)--(1,1);
  \draw[line width=1pt,-stealth](0,0)--(0.5,0.5);
     \end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
</image>
\end{center}
<li>
      <p> (Linearly Dependent Vectors) Two of the vectors are scalar multiples of each other. </p>
</li>
\begin{center}
<image width="100%">
   <shortdescription></shortdescription>
    <latex-image>
      \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
    \draw[line width=1pt,blue,-stealth](0,0)--(2,2);
  \draw[line width=1pt,red,-stealth](0,0)--(1,1);
  \draw[line width=1pt,-stealth](0,0)--(1,0);
     \end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
</image>
\end{center}
<li>
      <p> (Linearly Dependent Vectors) One vector can be viewed as the diagonal of a parallelogram determined by scalar multiples of the other two vectors.  All three vectors lie in the same plane. </p>
</li>
\begin{center}
<image width="100%">
   <shortdescription></shortdescription>
    <latex-image>
      \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
  \filldraw[blue, opacity=0.3](0,0)--(-2,2)--(2,4)--(4,2)--cycle;
\draw[line width=1pt,red,-stealth](0,0)--(2,1);
\draw[line width=1pt,red,-stealth, dashed](0,0)--(4,2);
  \draw[line width=1pt,blue,-stealth](0,0)--(-2,2);
  \draw[line width=1pt,-stealth](0,0)--(2,4); 
    \end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
</image>
\end{center}
<li>
      <p> (Linearly Independent Vectors)
A set of three vectors is linearly independent if the vectors do not lie in the same plane.  For example, vectors <m>\mathbf{i}</m>, <m>\mathbf{j}</m> and <m>\mathbf{k}</m> are linearly independent. </p>
</li>
</ul>
</p>
</subsubsection>
</subsection>







